The '''International Space Station Multilateral Coordination Board''' (MCB) is the highest-level cooperative body in the [[International Space Station]] programme. It was set up under the [[Memoranda of Understanding]] for the ISS,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esa.int/esapub/bulletin/bullet105/bul105_6.pdf|title=The Code of Conduct for International Space Station Crews|date=February 2001|author=A. Farand|work=ESA Bulletin|publisher=[[European Space Agency]]|accessdate=2015-11-29}}</ref> originally signed in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unoosa.org/pdf/pres/lsc2013/tech-05E.pdf|title=The Legal Framework for the International Space Station|publisher=United Nations Committee on the Peaceful Uses of Outer Space Legal Subcommittee|date= April 17, 2013|accessdate=2015-11-29}}</ref>

The MCB has members from each of the cooperating ISS partner organizations: [[NASA]], [[Roscosmos]], [[JAXA]], the [[European Space Agency]], and the [[Canadian Space Agency]]. The MCB sets policies for the ISS, including approving policies such as the [[Code of Conduct for International Space Station Crews]] that implement the [[International Space Station Intergovernmental Agreement]] that, together with the MOUs, provides the legal basis for the ISS program.

