'''John Nugent Fitch''' (24 October 1840–11 January 1927) was a British botanical illustrator and lithographer,<ref name=ODNB> {{Cite ODNB|id=54090|title=Fitch, Walter Hood (1817–1892)|last=Lewis|first=Jan}}</ref> best known for his contribution of 528 plates to ''The Orchid Album'',<ref>{{cite book|last1 = Moore|first1 = Thomas|author-link1 = Thomas Moore (botanist)|others = Illustrated by John Nugent Fitch|title = Orchid album :comprising coloured figures and descriptions of new, rare and beautiful orchidaceous plants|publisher = B. S. Williams|url = https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/bibliography/51750#}}, 10 volumes, (1882-1897)</ref> a landmark work of eleven volumes published between 1872 and 1897. Fitch was the nephew of botanical artist [[Walter Hood Fitch]] (1817-1892).<ref>St George, Ian, 1989 Botanical artists of New Zealand orchids: 2l. John Nugent Fitch (1843-1927). Orchids New Zealand 15. (3):73</ref> Fitch also contributed to [[Curtis's Botanical Magazine]] from 1878, joining a select group of illustrators such as [[William Kilburn]], [[James Sowerby]], [[Sydenham Edwards]], [[William Jackson Hooker]] and Walter Hood Fitch. Fitch also produced plates for ''[[Lepidoptera Indica]]''<ref>{{cite book| last1 = Moore| first1 = Frederic| author-link1 = Frederic Moore| last2 = Swinhoe| first2 = Charles | author-link2 = Charles Swinhoe| title = Lepidoptera indica | publisher = Reeve| url = https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/bibliography/51750#}}, 10 volumes, (1890-1913)</ref> by [[Frederic Moore]].
Fitch was elected a fellow of the [[Linnean Society]] in 1877.<ref name=ODNB/>
